%S A093811 1,3,4,7,6,12,8,15,13,8,2,18,4,14,14,21,8,29,10,12,13,8,7,34,16,18,27,
%T A093811 34,19,22,4,27,14,22,28,53,22,36,34,20,5,33,13,28,43,33,29,72,44,18,
%U A093811 16,32,16,63,32,72,48,61,46,28,7,18,40,51,39,62,43,74,64,34,8,83,22,52,59
%N A093811 Sum of the digital products of the divisors of n.
%C A093811 The first few n such that a(n) = n are: 1, 14, 27, 156, 196. Are there any more?
%C A093811 No more up to 10^8. Up to there, a(798) = 933 is the last point with a(n) > n. Are there others? - _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 05 2026
%C A093811 We conjecture that a(n) < n for all n > 798, and that n = 10^k - 4 and n = 10^k - 2 set new record values of a(n) ~ 94*9^(k-2) resp. 9^k*4/3 for all k (resp. k > 4), hence lim sup a(n)/n = 0. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 11 2026
%H A093811 Harvey P. Dale, <a href="/A093811/b093811.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%F A093811 Inverse Moebius transform of A007954. a(n) = A007954 * A000012(n), where operation * denotes Dirichlet convolution for n >= 1. Dirichlet convolution of functions b(n), c(n) is (b * c)(n) = Sum_{d|n} b(d)*c(n/d). Also, a * A008683 = A007954 (n >= 1). - _Jaroslav Krizek_, Mar 22 2009; edited by _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 05 2026
%F A093811 Conjecture: lim sup_{n -> oo} a(n)/9^log_10(n) = lim_{k -> oo} a(10^k - 2)/9^k = 4/3. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 11 2026
%e A093811 a(1234) = 69 because the divisors of 1234 are: [1, 2, 617, 1234] and 1 + 2 + 6*1*7 + 1*2*3*4 = 69.
%p A093811 A093811 := proc(n::integer)
%p A093811     local a,d ;
%p A093811     a := 0 ;
%p A093811     for d in numtheory[divisors](n) do
%p A093811         a := a+A007954(d) ;
%p A093811     end do:
%p A093811 end proc: # _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 02 2019
%t A093811 Table[Total[Times@@IntegerDigits[#]&/@Divisors[n]],{n,100}] (* _Harvey P. Dale_, Jun 02 2022 *)
%o A093811 (PARI) apply( {A093811(n)=sumdiv(n, d, vecprod(digits(d)))}, [1..77]) \\ _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 05 2026
%Y A093811 Cf. A007954 (product of digits), A008683 (Möbius function mu).
%K A093811 base,easy,nonn,changed
%O A093811 1,2
